widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">After examining the above phy=
sical quantities, we see that kilowatt hours and kilowatts are both common =
units. One is a unit of </span><b>energy</b><span style=3D"font-weight: 400=
;">, and the other is a unit of </span><b>power</b><span style=3D"font-weig=
ht: 400;">. To understand the conversion relationship between them, we must=
 first introduce another variable: operating time (T). The specific convers=
ion formula is:</span></p><p><i><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">P (kW) =
=3D E (kWh) =C3=B7 T (h)</span></i></p><p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"=
>In this formula, E is energy consumed over the period that the appliance i=
s in operation. P is the power rating of the appliance in kW. T is the time=
 in hours of operation. Based on this relationship, the kWh to kW conversio=
n can be expressed as:</span></p><p><i><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">kW=
 =3D kWh =C3=B7 hr</span></i></p><p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">To he=
lp you in understanding and using this formula, here is an example. Assume =
you choose an air conditioner with 1.5kW power that will be operated for 5 =
hours each day. To find the daily energy usage, multiply the power of the u=
nit times the hours. For example, 1.5kW x 5h =3D 7.5kWh. This information c=
an help determine if the energy usage is within the capacity of your system=
.</span></p>								</div>
				</div>
					</div>
				</div>
